# app

The HINT (Human Intent Native Transpiler) command-line tool is a lightweight, zero-dependency compiler. It reads local repository architectures, aggregates cascading file configurations, processes structural block directives, and outputs an ultra-dense, markdown-formatted system prompt optimized for LLM coding assistants.

Runnable as npx cli command like `npx @openhint/cli` and register also executable file to run it more simpler way just like `hint ...`.

# lang

TypeScript (Node.js v22+ / ESM). The compiled output is a single ESM entry point executed directly by Node.js through the `bin` field of `package.json`.

# deps

- `@openhint/transpiler` — the sole runtime dependency; provides `parse`, `compile`, and the `is` error predicate.
- No additional runtime packages. Use only Node.js built-in modules for process I/O.

# build

- `make build-js` to compile TypeScript to the release directory.
- `make test-js` to run the vitest suite.

# rule

- Write nothing to stdout except the final compiled prompt string.
- Write all diagnostic messages, usage text, and error details exclusively to stderr.
- Exit code 0 on success; exit code 1 on any failure.
- Never swallow an error silently — always emit the message before exiting.

# read {applications/cli/commands/default.ts.hint} as DefaultCommand

The default compile-and-output command. Invoked when no sub-command name is present in argv. Exports `executeDefault(filePaths: string[]): Promise<string>`.

# read {applications/cli/commands/validate.ts.hint} as ValidateCommand

The specification-review command. Invoked when the first argv token is `validate`. Prepends a structured critique directive so the LLM reviews the spec rather than implementing it. Exports `executeValidate(filePaths: string[]): Promise<string>`.

# read {applications/cli/commands/claude.ts.hint} as ClaudeCommand

The Claude CLI integration command. Invoked when the first argv token is `claude`. Compiles files and pipes the prompt to the `claude` CLI. Exports `executeClaude(filePaths: string[]): Promise<void>`.

# read {applications/cli/commands/codex.ts.hint} as CodexCommand

The Codex CLI integration command. Invoked when the first argv token is `codex`. Compiles files and pipes the prompt to the `codex` CLI. Exports `executeCodex(filePaths: string[]): Promise<void>`.

# read {applications/cli/commands/config.ts.hint} as ConfigCommand

The agent config command. Invoked when the first argv token is `config`. Locates the project root and appends HINT integration instructions to `AGENTS.md` and `CLAUDE.md`. Exports `executeConfig(projectRoot?: string): Promise<void>`.

# function run

## arg filePaths: string[]

Resolved file path arguments after the optional command name has been stripped from argv. Empty only when `command === "config"` with no explicit path.

## arg command: string | undefined

The sub-command name extracted from argv, or `undefined` for the default behavior. Accepted values: `"validate"`, `"claude"`, `"codex"`, `"config"`.

## return Promise<void>

Exits the process before returning on every code path.

## error UsageError

`command !== "config"` and `filePaths` is empty (only a command name was given with no file paths). Print usage to stderr and exit 1.

## error AppError

The transpiler threw a structured HINT error (parse, I/O, or reference error), or a spawned agent binary was not found. Print `error.message` to stderr and exit 1.

## flow

1. If `command !== "config"` and `filePaths` is empty, print usage to stderr and exit 1.
2. Wrap steps 3–10 in a single try/catch; on any error print to stderr and exit 1.
3. If `command === "config"`, call `executeConfig(filePaths[0])` from {ConfigCommand} and exit 0.
4. If `command === "claude"`, call `executeClaude(filePaths)` from {ClaudeCommand} and exit 0.
5. If `command === "codex"`, call `executeCodex(filePaths)` from {CodexCommand} and exit 0.
6. If `command === "validate"`, call `executeValidate(filePaths)` from {ValidateCommand}.
7. Otherwise call `executeDefault(filePaths)` from {DefaultCommand}.
8. If the returned string is empty, exit 0 without writing to stdout.
9. Write the string followed by a single trailing newline to `process.stdout`.
10. Exit 0.
